images.title: Peter Church / Brigg End, Filey
images.caption: Brigg End. This view is essentially east from the end of the cliff top walk. Just visible on the southeast horizon are the chalk cliffs of Flamborough Head and Bempton Cliffs.

images.title: David Pickersgill / Rock pools on Filey Brig
images.caption: Rock pools on Filey Brigg. This is the flat rock bed which the layer of boulder clay that forms the main part of the promontory sits on. The surface is dappled by rock pools, probably cut into the rock by water repeatedly swirling pebbles round.

images.title: Filey Brigg - view to Carr Nase by John S Turner, CC BY-SA 2.0 <https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/2.0>, via Wikimedia Commons
images.caption: View to Carr Nase

images.title: Barry Hoggart / Boulder clay cliffs of Filey Brigg
images.caption: Boulder clay cliffs. The deeply serrated cliffs are of soft boulder clay left behind by the retreating ice at the end of the last ice age. They rest on a firm platform of older Jurassic sedimentary rocks.

description: This super country park is located on the coast at Filey in North Yorkshire. It is also known as North Cliff Country Park. The elevated position of the park provides splendid views over Filey Bay and the town below. The walk also takes you along Filey Brigg - a long narrow peninsula with steep cliffs and lovely coastal views. The Cleveland Way and the Centenary Way walking routes run past the park so there is scope for continuing your walk along the coast to the nearby town of Scarborough. The Scarborough to Filey Walk gives more details on this stretch of coast which is one of the finest in the country.

details.subtitle: Pubs/Cafes
details.content: There's an on site cafe where you can enjoy a good range of refreshments.

details.subtitle: Dog Walking
details.content: The park is dog friendly and a popular spot for dog walkers.

details.subtitle: Further Information and Other Local Ideas
details.content: The park is great for wildlife with lots of seabirds on the rocks and seals, whales and dolphins to see in the waters below. There's also a good sized car park. To continue your walking in the area pick up the Filey to Bridlington Walk and visit the wonderful Bempton Cliffs where you'll find an RSPB bird reserve with thousands of birds to see.
